/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

you are making the same mistake as the redditors. MOST of finance is not bullshit. there are some niche areas where bs happens due to new technology or lax regulation, and there is some money made in pure speculation or high frequency trading, but that is only the very tip of the iceberg - its the most VISIBLE part of finance because its flashy, exciting, and seemingly involves people making money based on nothing.

but the vast majority of finance is still based on very basic things with a basis in reality. Corporations do still have their stocks tank if they do badly, because if the company goes under or has to sell itself at a discount, anyone still holding stock will take a loss. Its not a lottery or totally detached from reality for MOST of the market. But redditors (and you) only look at the most exciting BS parts and declare the whole thing BS on that basis.

Like with gamestop - redditors saw hedge funds "shorting" gamestop. They, being retarded, thought this "shorting" was what CAUSED the price of a stock to go down, and the company to suffer, and thought that this happened solely at the whim of stock market players.

Rather, in reality, gamestop is a shitty company that will probably soon go bankrupt, so people were betting on its stocks going down, that is to say "shorting" it.

Now the extent to which redditors have a point is that, if it becomes common knowledge that "everyone" is shorting gamestop, that does sort of create a general feeling that ganestop is sure to fail. But at the same time, if too many people want to get in on shorting gamestop, it will at some point become profitable to bet the other way, on the off chance gamestop turns things around. Which is what redditors did, en masse. And it paid off for some of them, but it paid off 10x more for real investors that took the same position they did
